snippet.textDisplay: OBVIOUSLY things with the company are being handled correctly and safely WE DONT want to discuss legalities about the company because this isn’t about the company, it’s about Loren’s story and raising awareness for these type of conditions and letting people know they’re not alone. Thank you guys for being so concerned but I promise we have a whole team helping us in terms of the legalities with the company. I’m sorry the music is so loud I’ve never made a YouTube before and I’m still learning. Please just respect what we are doing with our own personal lives that we decided to share with you guys. We love all the support we’ve gotten but please just don’t worry about the company this isn’t about them ❤️ Also, for those asking why we need a go fund me if the company is taking care of us- lawsuits/settlements/proposals... those take a while... so it’s convenient having a source of income outside of the Workman comp checks until that agreement is reached! I haven’t worked since the accident and Loren’s loss of wage checks don’t cover all of our bills... we have our own apartment, car, insurance, phones... and we used to have double income to pay these things. So the gofundme me helps with so many things outside of what might not be covered by the company or Workman comp..

snippet.textDisplay:
There are several examples of people without lower bodies who had very successful lives. Cheryl Sparks was one of the drones in the 1972 SciFi Film "Silent Running". Cheryl had no lower body, but enjoyed horseback riding, surfing, water skiing, swimming, etc. Other actors that played drones in that movie who also had no lower bodies were Mark Persons, Steven Brown, and Larry Whisenhunt. The maker of the movie "Silent Running" was Doug Trumbull, and he got the idea for the drones from the 1932 movie "Freaks", which featured John Eckhardt Jr, who had no lower body, but ran very easily on his hands/arms. John put on a stage show act with his twin brother where they did the "saw the man in half" routine. John's brother would lay on the table, and then switch places with John and a dwarf who was inside a pair of pants. They would "saw" John in half, and his lower body (the dwarf) would get up and run around on the stage, with John chasing after his "legs", with John running on his hands/arms. John Eckhardt was also famous for doing one-armed handstands. You can see John running and jumping easily on his arms/hands if you look up the movie "Freaks".
So a long story short, as one article about John Eckhardt states, "never judge a person by their appearance".
Best of luck to you. The people I mention above prove that you can have a full and active life regardless of your handicap.
It is all about what is in your heart really.
What an impressive and admirable young man this it. His spirit is really inspirational.
